<p><b>Yakuza</b> <span style="font-weight: normal">(<span class="t_nihongo_kanji"><span lang="ja" xml:lang="ja">ヤクザ or やくざ</span></span> <span class="t_nihongo_help noprint"><sup><a href="/wiki/Help:Japanese" title="Help:Japanese"><span class="t_nihongo_icon" style="color: #00e; font: bold 80% sans-serif; text-decoration: none; padding: 0 .1em;">?</span></a></sup></span>)</span>, also known as <b>gokudō</b> <span style="font-weight: normal">(<span class="t_nihongo_kanji"><span lang="ja" xml:lang="ja">極道</span></span> <span class="t_nihongo_help noprint"><sup><a href="/wiki/Help:Japanese" title="Help:Japanese"><span class="t_nihongo_icon" style="color: #00e; font: bold 80% sans-serif; text-decoration: none; padding: 0 .1em;">?</span></a></sup></span>)</span>, are members of traditional <a href="/wiki/Organized_crime" title="Organized crime">organized crime</a> groups in <a href="/wiki/Japan" title="Japan">Japan</a>, and also known as "violence groups".</p>
<p>Today, the Yakuza are among the largest crime organizations in the world. In Japan, as of 2005, there are some 86,300 known members.<sup id="cite_ref-NPA_0-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-NPA-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> In Japanese legal terminology, yakuza organizations are referred to as <i><a href="/wiki/B%C5%8Dryokudan" title="Bōryokudan">bōryokudan</a></i>, literally "violence groups", which Yakuza members consider an insult as it can be applied to any violent criminal.</p>
