<tr>
<td><b><a href="/wiki/Toa-kai" title="Toa-kai">Toua Yuai Jigyo Kumiai</a></b><br />
<span style="font-weight: normal">(<span class="t_nihongo_kanji"><span lang="ja" xml:lang="ja">東亜友愛事業組合</span></span> <span class="t_nihongo_help noprint"><sup><a href="/wiki/Help:Japanese" title="Help:Japanese"><span class="t_nihongo_icon" style="color: #00e; font: bold 80% sans-serif; text-decoration: none; padding: 0 .1em;">?</span></a></sup></span>)</span>, sometimes called Tōa-kai <span style="font-weight: normal">(<span class="t_nihongo_kanji"><span lang="ja" xml:lang="ja">東亜会</span></span> <span class="t_nihongo_help noprint"><sup><a href="/wiki/Help:Japanese" title="Help:Japanese"><span class="t_nihongo_icon" style="color: #00e; font: bold 80% sans-serif; text-decoration: none; padding: 0 .1em;">?</span></a></sup></span>)</span></td>
<td>Founded by <a href="/wiki/Hisayuki_Machii" title="Hisayuki Machii">Hisayuki Machii</a> in 1948, the Tao Yuai Jigyo Kumiai yakuza family quickly became one of most influential yakuza groups in <a href="/wiki/Tokyo" title="Tokyo">Tokyo</a>. It is composed of yakuza of Korean origin, and numbers more than 1,000 divided into 6 clans. Its current oyabun is <a href="/w/index.php?title=Satoru_Nomura&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Satoru Nomura (page does not exist)">Satoru Nomura</a>.</td>
